Males and females rest on vegetation with their wings open (
Figure 39
), and come readily to flowers. Some- is probably also true of most Pyrginae which rest with their wings flat. Flight is rapid, and difficult to follow, but individuals often return to the same perch. The ovipositing female rests with her wings held upwards at a slight angle, and the abdomen angled downwards (87/15).
